# Background Tasks in FastAPI
================================

What are Background Tasks and why do we need them?


Web APIs follow a simple lifecycle:
Client → Request → Server processes → Response → Connection closed

Now imagine an endpoint where I need to send email, generate pdf, etc.
What if:
Email sending takes 5 seconds
PDF generation takes 10 seconds
Now your API response takes 15+ seconds.

Problems:
    User waits
    Browser may timeout
    Server thread is blocked
    Poor UX
    Poor scalability

Hence, we need to separate

🟢 Critical work → Must complete before responding
🔵 Non-critical work → Can happen after response

Example:
Critical	        Background
Save user in DB	    Send email
Validate request	Generate report
Verify payment	    Send notification

==========================================================

We have a built in FastAPI Background task, which works internally as follows :
    Task is added to a list
    After response is sent
    FastAPI executes it in the same process

But we have limitations : 
    It still runs in the same server
    If server crashes → task is lost
    Not distributed
    No retry mechanism

Hence we use Celery. 

==========================================================

Celery : 
Celery is a powerful, production-ready asynchronous job queue, which allows you to run time-consuming Python functions in the background.
The internal working of Celery can be stated as the Producer/Consumer model  : 

Producer
Producers are basically web services that handle web requests.
During the request processing, the time-taking tasks or the periodic tasks are pushed into the message queue.

Queue
Celery communicates via messages, usually using a broker to mediate between clients and workers. To initiate a task the client adds a message to the queue(the broker) and then delivers that message to a worker. Here the queue can be referred to as Redis, RabbitMQ, or many other services supported by Celery.

Consumers
Consumers are the worker nodes. The main difference between the web and worker is that web nodes receive requests from the internet and place tasks to be processed asynchronously in the queue and worker nodes are the machines that pick these tasks and execute them.

==========================================================

High level idea of what we weill be doing : 
Let's take example of when the user sign’s up on the particular website and receives an verification email.

After receiving the client’s request the server enqueues a new task(python function to send email) in the Redis(an in-memory data store) which works as a message queue.
These tasks will not run on our main FastAPI webserver. Instead, Celery will manage separate servers that can run the tasks simultaneously in the background.
The Celery worker picks up the task from the queue and executes it asynchronously which enables the web application to respond quickly to the request.
Whenever a new task arrives, one worker picks it up and processes it.
Hence celery decreased the performance load from web application by running the functionality of the server asynchronously.

==========================================================

Understanding deeper how celery works : 

Client request -> Uvicorn server -> Validation and store into the database -> FastAPI adds the task to the queue -> Response is sent back to the client.
Now, we will be having a celery worker running infinitely, which will look for tasks in the redis, if found, it picks up and the worker executes the task. 
If response is configured, it gets stored in the redis, or else the response is not stored. So, in this way our server need not wait. The tasks are scheduled and executed when are workers are free. 

This is what make our task go into the redis --> send_email_task.delay("abc@gmail.com") 

A series of steps happen internally : 
Step 1: Task Serialization

    Celery converts:
    send_email_task("abc@gmail.com")

    Into:

    {
    "task": "tasks.send_email_task",
    "id": "random-uuid",
    "args": ["abc@gmail.com"],
    "kwargs": {}
    }

    This is serialized (usually JSON). We do this as worker accepts json.

Step 2: Push to Broker (Redis)

    That serialized message is stored in: Redis

    Inside Redis:
    It goes into a queue list
    Stored in memory
    Persistent (if configured)

    Now FastAPI is DONE.
    Response sent.

Step 3: Worker Polling

    Celery Worker process (separate process):
    Constantly listens to Redis
    Polls queue
    When task appears
    Pulls it

    Worker is started using: Celery

Step 4: Task Execution

    Worker:
    Deserializes message
    Finds function path
    Imports module
    Executes function
    Stores result in backend (Redis or DB)

==========================================================

Async vs Background Tasks

Even if you use: async def endpoint():

It does NOT mean:
    CPU heavy tasks become fast
    Long tasks become safe

Async only helps with I/O concurrency.
CPU-heavy tasks still block.
Celery solves that by moving work to separate processes.

